When Graham Fuller of Voice of America invited Nimat to the United States to serve as a U.S. Department of State Exchange Ambassador, Nimat began to see even more opportunities. She became a wife, mother, and daughter-in-law. And as she acquired internationally recognized security and well-being programming and best practices, she was asked to share her knowledge at the largest conference for girls in 2014. Since then, Nimat’s work has been featured in news outlets around the world and she has been honored with an award from the Women’s World Summit Foundation.

“I do my work with what I know from the things I have been through—a lot has happened. I am an adult and I am Sierra Leonean, but I can speak for the people,” said Nimat. “We need to talk about it and tell the truth to the next generation. There must be consequences for sexual perpetrators. If convicted, they should be registered in a database that identifies them as sexual offenders. You must be responsible for your actions.”
